\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I took little notice of the fact that she had been apparently stuffing herself,
 probably having a bad case of the munchies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I said 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Yeah, Eileen,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 managing to keep my tone of voice even, normal-sounding.
 It really felt like biting the bullet when I said 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

it's me, Papa-Bear
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 It also made me cringe as the connotations that old term of endearment
 implied flashed across my mind's eye.
 Jesus Christ, not Eileen.
 What was I doing? Was there no other way? Was this a possible way out or
 was it just a faster way under?
\end_layout

